"The sea is ours": The enclave Bolivia hopes the court will reopen its path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol the fully equipped naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings there are blue flags.
On the bases of the navy from Lake Titicaka to the Amazon is written the slogan: "The sea belongs to us rightfully.
It's our duty to get her back."
Throughout the landlocked Bolivia, the memory of Chile’s coastline after a bloody conflict over the exploitation of natural resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the longing of its people to travel to the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have now increased more than ever, for decades, as Bolivia has been awaiting the ruling of the International Court of Justice on 1 October after five years of consultation.
"Bolivia has the dynamic, a spirit of unity and calmness, and naturally awaits the result with a positive look," said Roberto Calzadila, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the International Court's decision on large screens across the country, hoping that The Hague tribunal will decide in favour of Bolivia's claim to force Chile, after decades of fickle talks, to negotiate for Bolivia to be granted a sovereign exit to the sea.
