John Edward: Language Skills Are Necessary For People of the World · Global Voices
The independent schools of Scotland have a history of academic excellence, which continued in 2018, with yet another series of excellent results in the exams, which were only further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Council (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible level of service to their students and parents.
The aim of independent schools is to prepare their students for the next and higher levels of education, the career they will choose and their position as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a school curriculum on demand, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable choice lesson in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you're talking to someone in a language he understands, then what you're saying gets into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, what you say comes into his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot simply rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's exams, we find that languages are at the top of the scoreboards, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of foreign - language students achieved a degree of A.
Data gathered from 74 schools of SCIS members showed that 72 percent of students achieved a degree of A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also had a grade A.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed for children and young people in the future.
Languages today, as a course of choice, are considered as important as courses related to science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A UK Employment and Skills Committee survey in 2014 revealed that, as regards the reasons why employers had difficulty filling job vacancies, 17 per cent involved a lack of language skills.
Therefore, the need to acquire language skills is becoming increasingly urgent so that young people are prepared for their future careers.
Since more future employment opportunities require language knowledge, these skills are necessary in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future, because of this skill that you can use throughout your life.
If someone is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically this multilingual person will have an advantage over competition.
According to YouGov's survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, while French was the only language that spoke a two-digit percentage of respondents (15 percent).
For this reason, investing in language teaching today is important for today's children.
Knowledge of many languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child may be interested in, there will always be some languages to choose from in independent schools, which have specialized teaching staff in this area.
The independent schools of Scotland are loyally providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to achieve, whatever the future holds for them.
One cannot deny today that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of the country, so this reality should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturalism and excellence for young people in Scotland.
They have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
