North Korea says it won't be disarmed unilaterally without confidence measures.
The Secretary of State of North Korea told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions deepen the feeling of distrust towards the United States and that his country would not unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons under such conditions.
Ri Yong Ho stated at the annual general meeting of the global organisation that North Korea had taken "significant steps of goodwill" in the past year, e.g. the cessation of nuclear and ballistic tests, the dismantling of nuclear testing facilities and the commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the US," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and under such conditions there is no way to unilaterally start our disarmament."
While Ri repeated known complaints from North Korea about Washington's resistance to the possibility of a "staged" approach to denuclearisation, according to which North Korea would be rewarded as it progressed gradually in the process, his statement was important in that it did not completely rule out unilateral denuclearisation, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to the joint communiqué of Kim Young Eun and Donald Trump at the first summit to take place between an active US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12th, when Kim promised to work on "denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking to officially end the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first deliver its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted calls for relaxation of the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on becoming "first denuclearisation" and increasing pressure by threatening sanctions to achieve their goal by blackmailing, even putting obstacles in the "end of the war" declaration," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri made no mention of a planned second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US chief pointed out to the United Nations earlier this week.
The minister, however, pointed out three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the partner in the issue of denuclearisation were South Korea and not the US, denuclearizing the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
Even so, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from last year, when he told the United Nations General Assembly that targeting the U.S. inland with North Korean ballistic missiles was inevitable because "Bad President" Trump called Kim a "missileman" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who was threatening last year to destroy North Korea completely, praised Kim for his courage to move forward with disarmament measures, but said that much still needs to be done and that sanctions should remain in force until North Korea is denuclearised.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this, saying "If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures it has taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue intensively and continuously until full, final and confirmed denuclearisation is achieved."
The Security Council unanimously approved the sanctions for North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to counteract the funding of Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the margins of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
