Harvard students attend classes on how to rest a lot
This year, a new course at Harvard University seeks all undergraduate students to sleep more in an effort to combat the growing culture of overnight study by consuming a lot of caffeine.
An academic discovered that students at the number one university worldwide often do not know basic things, e.g. how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chisler, Professor of Medical Sleep at Harvard Medical School and a qualified doctor at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of his kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the lesson after a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why am I just hearing about this in my last year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - something that surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, which began for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as to improving general well-being.
Paul Bareira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to include the course when it was found that students were sleep deprived during the week to a significant extent.
The hourly course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is the image of a student dormitory, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books, to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, as well as the importance of sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn how long - term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not directly change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have the right to know the health effects when you choose to smoke," Professor Chisler added.
The culture of boasting because you studied all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Enough sleep, good quality, should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, exhaustion and stress, he said, even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in a state of starvation, resulting in a lasting feeling of hunger.
Raymond Shaw, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physics biology, helped Professor Chisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said his lesson opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a lesson all over campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar program before starting their studies in this highly competitive educational institution.
Professor Chisler advised students to set up an alert for the time they should go to sleep, as well as an alarm clock for the waking hour, and to be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic monitors and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
