Other important features are that the frequency of maintenance work is reduced, as it will be possible to use new frigates for up to two years outside German ports.
However, constant delays mean that although warships are considered state-of-the-art, which will allow Germany to show its power abroad, until they are finally put on duty, they will already be obsolete, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to pick up the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy returned a ship to a shipyard after delivery.
Not much information has been made available about the reasons for the return, but the German media have reported a series of important "software and hardware defects" that would put the warship out of use if it were used on a combat mission.
The problems of the software were particularly important as Baden-Wuerttemberg class ships have a crew of about 120 sailors, only half compared to the oldest Bremen class frigates.
It has also been revealed that the ship has much greater weight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The frigate Rheinland-Pfalz of 7,000 tonnes is believed to have twice the weight of similar class ships used by Germans during World War II.
