National Trust eavesdrops on the secret life of bats
New research carried out on an estate in the Highlands, Scotland, seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting their food.
The findings will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and will contribute to the planning of future actions to protect the environment.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will explore the habits of the common nano- bat and the small bat, as well as the brown bat and the dompenton myoctic in Inverewe Gardens, in Wester Ross.
Recorders will be placed in key locations around the estate to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NTS personnel and volunteers will also carry out mobile searches using handheld detectors.
Analysing the sound of all recordings by experts will determine the frequency of bat calls, as well as what species have this behavior.
A biotope map and a report will then be created to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a natural environment protection consultant for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of biotope management, such as the creation of meadows and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have fallen significantly since the last century.
They are threatened by building and development projects affecting the places where they roost and destroy their habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting are also a danger, as are tape adhesives for flies and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't actually blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes to catch their prey.
They're using an advanced sound-location technique to detect insects and obstacles in the course of their flight.
NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, considers bats very important.
It has ten trained experts, who conduct regular investigations, inspect the places where bats roost and sometimes rescue them.
The organization has also created Scotland's first and only shelter exclusively for bats on the Threave estate, Damfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten species live.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, states that the estate is the perfect ground for bats.
"Here in Threeve we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many large trees and an ideal habitat.
There is still much we do not know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to increase their populations."
It emphasises that it is important to check for bats first before any maintenance work in dwellings, as the destruction of a single nest with small ones could kill up to 400 females and young, possibly eliminating the entire local population.
Bats are protected species and it is forbidden to kill them, harass them, or disturb their privacy, or destroy their nests.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a member of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, encouraged the public to offer their help.
He said: "There's a lot left to learn about our bats and many of our species, we just don't know how their population is developing."
