Europe locks victory at the Ryder Cup in Paris
The team of Europe won the Ryder 2018 Cup, defeating the US team with a final score of 16.5 against 10.5 on the Le Golf National golf course, outside Paris in France.
The American team has now been defeated six consecutive times on European soil and has won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained its first place, as the team of Danish chief Thomas Bjorn reached 14 and a half points needed to defeat the United States.
US team star Phil Mikkelston, who fought hard during the tournament, threw his shot into the water at par-3 16th hole, giving the victory to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari flashed in all of his rounds and thus became one of the four players who achieved 5-0-0 since the start of today's tournament in 1979.
American Jordan Spith was defeated at 5&4 by the lowest in the European team's rankings, Danish Thorbjorn Olsen.
The best ranking player in the world, Dustin Johnson, scored 2 and 1 against Ian Pulter from England, who may have played his last game in the Ryder Cup.
Spanish veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Sergio Garcia, was crowned the most victorious European of all time in the tournament with a total score of 25.5.
"I usually don't cry, but today I can't help myself.
It's been a tough year.
I'm grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so glad we got the cup back.
It's all about the team and I'm glad I could help," Garcia said moved after the European victory.
He gives the baton to John Ram's compatriot, who defeated the American golf legend Tiger Woods 2&1 in an atomic game on Sunday.
"I feel incredible pride in beating Tiger Woods, I grew up admiring this guy," said 23-year-old Ram.
Woods lost all four matches in France and now has a career record at the Ryder 13-21-3 Cup.
Unusual statistics for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 major titles and has only been surpassed by Jack Niklaus.
The U.S. team has had a hard time finding a target all weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas, and Tony Finno, who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
US Chief Jim Farik spoke after his team's disappointing performance, "I'm proud of these kids, they fought it.
At times this morning we pushed Europe hard enough.
We fought hard.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a big leader.
All 12 of his players played very well.
We'll regroup, work with the US PGA and the Ryder Cup Commission and move forward.
I love those 12 kids, and I'm proud to be their leader.
We have to face it.
They were better than us."
Information on the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in the provinces of Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest communication from Florida’s Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general drop in Red Tide gatherings for parts of Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of heterogeneous spots are observed in regions of the provinces of Pinella, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
A spill of Red Tide spans about 130 miles of coastline from the northern province of Pinella to the southern province of Li.
Spots are located about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less places than last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in Pasco Province.
Moderate concentrations were recorded on the coast and off the coast of Pinela province last week, low to high concentrations were recorded off the coast in Hillsboro province, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manati province, background concentrations to high concentrations on the coast or off the coast in Sarasota province, background concentrations to moderate concentrations in Charlotte province, background concentrations to high concentrations on the coast or off the coast in Li province and low concentrations in Collier province.
Respiratory disturbance continues to be recorded in the provinces of Pinella, Manati, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
No respiratory disturbances were reported in northwestern Florida in the last week.
